<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-01-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="315" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d315">
                    <head>No. 314.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Schuyler</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-01-05"><hi rend="italic">January</hi> 5,
                            1883</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 15.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I herewith inclose a copy of a dispatch,<note n="*" xml:id="d315fn1">See Mr. Heap to Mr. Frelinghuysen, No. 147,
                            December 2, 1882, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>.</note> No. 147, of the 2d
                        ultimo, received from Mr. Heap, chargé at Constantinople, in which he
                        informs the Department of the release from imprisonment by the Sultan, at
                        the request of Mr. Wallace, of five Greeks.</p>
                    <p>You may inform the Greek Government of the facts, as evincing the friendship
                        of the United States for that country.</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>